3. Port ST-T1024 to the Target MCU

Step 1: Clone and Validate

```bash
# Clone the standard repository
git clone https://github.com/actuing/ST-T1024-STANDARD-FOR-EMBEDDED-LLM.git
cd ST-T1024-STANDARD-FOR-EMBEDDED-LLM

# Run the emulator to understand the pipeline
python3 IMPROVED-EMULATOR-of-ST-T1024/improved_st_t1024_v2.1.py
```

Expected output: 400 cycles | 800ns | Power State: OFF (0V)

Step 2: Port the Core Modules

Module File Porting Effort Notes
Intent Harvesting intent_harvesting.h Low — standard C Text normalization
Ternary FIS fis_triage.h Medium — optimize rule base Extend with synonyms
FSM Scheduler fsm_scheduler.h Medium — hardware timers SysTick or cycle counter
Ternary Engine ternary_engine.h Low — pure addition/subtraction No FPU needed
Tile Memory tile_memory.h High — MCU-specific ROM/SRAM layout
Power Gating power_gating.h High — MCU-specific PMU registers

Step 3: MCU-Specific Optimizations

For ARM Cortex-M4/M33:

```c
// Enable cache for deterministic access
SCB_EnableICache();
SCB_EnableDCache();

// Configure MPU to protect ROM (immutable) and SRAM
MPU_Region_Init(MPU_REGION_ROM, ROM_BASE, MPU_SIZE_2MB, 
                MPU_AP_READ_ONLY, MPU_REGION_ENABLE);
MPU_Region_Init(MPU_REGION_SRAM, SRAM_BASE, MPU_SIZE_512KB,
                MPU_AP_READ_WRITE, MPU_REGION_ENABLE);

// Set SysTick timer for FSM cycle counting
SysTick_Config(SystemCoreClock / 1000000); // 1 µs tick
```

For RISC-V (NEORV32/PULPino):

```assembly
# Custom RISC-V instruction: TERNARY_XNOR rd, rs1, rs2
# Performs XNOR on ternary vectors in rs1 and rs2
inline ternary_t ternary_xnor_insn(ternary_t a, ternary_t b) {
    register ternary_t result;
    __asm__ volatile (
        ".insn r 0x0B, 0x0, 0x0, %0, %1, %2"
        : "=r"(result)
        : "r"(a), "r"(b)
    );
    return result;
}
```

